Heat loss to the surroundings via the open top surface of the mug occurs through convection and radiation:
  - Convection: $dot(Q) = alpha A Delta T$
  - Radiation: $dot(Q) = sigma A epsilon_"eff" (T^4 - T_0^4)$
  
  By mixing the cold milk into the hot coffee immediately, the fluid's initial temperature drops. This instantly reduces the temperature difference ($Delta T$) relative to the ambient air. Because the driving temperature gradient is smaller throughout the entire waiting period—and radiation drops significantly due to its fourth-power temperature dependence—the total heat lost to the environment is minimized, resulting in a higher final temperature.